
* implement TASK_STOPPED
    get the client to recognize
    it, make sure we can run programs really quickly, etc.
    That also lets us write some unit tests using the Python client to
    run small programs to completion & examine their outputs.

* implement multitasking
    * timer interrupt
        Let's have this be the only interrupt?..
        Keeps things super simple: the kernel just loops through all tasks,
        feeding them input if they need it, maybe running them for a bit,
        then handling their output if any.
        Will we be ok without the UART receive interrupt?.. I think so, as
        long as our kernel's loop is fast enough.
    * context switching
        * r22 - r25 and Z need to be saved during context switches
        * task->free should be updated to X on context switch
    * run queue
        ...OR, can we cheat for now?.. I wanted to get this project done in
        a week, but figuring out how to assign to the dang stack pointer
        slowed me down... can we forget about resource queues for now, and
        just have a timer interrupt which switches execution to the next
        task whose state is RUNNING?.. so, we just cycle through the task
        table.
        And then for reading/writing, we uhhhh just have the tasks disable
        interrupts while they do it?..
        Hmmmm no, that would be gross.
        But ok, let's do this simple "cycle through tasks" approach for now,
        but not implement UART stuff for tasks yet.
        Instead, let's just make sure we can see multiple tasks blinking the
        LED at different rates, for now.

* resource queues
    * run queue
    * sleep queue (each entry needs an associated time?..)
    * uart read/write queues

* improve the usage of stack by interrupts!.. currently they use currently running
  task's stack, which is wasteful, since every task needs to keep a bunch of stack
  space clear in case an interrupt needs it!..
  see also the comment in the INTERRUPTS section of minitasks.c
